editorial_summary.overview: Constantly evolving art installation, playground & discovery center made from found objects.

properties.formatted_address: 750 N 16th St, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA
properties.name: City Museum

reviews.text: Amazing place for everyone. Toddlers to bigger kids to teenagers and adults. You could spend hours here and keep finding amazing things. The food isn't crazy experience either so you can spend the day here. They were super great with our large group over the weekend. We had about 90 people in our group and they were super accommodating and there were no issues.

You have got to take your children here! I visited as the parent of adult children. I wish I had taken my kids here. This place is amazing. Be sure to give your kids a quiet break every once in a while because it’s really overwhelming for little ones. The employees are polite and thoughtful and knowledgeable. There’s something for everybody here to see or enjoy. The views from the rooftop are nice. The young man running the Ferris wheel day I visited was very entertaining and really seemed to enjoy his job. I wish someone would check on the antique cabinets because items are falling off the front of the shelves. I’m looking forward to returning

The most redeeming quality of this place is all of the stuff that has been kept out of a landfill.  Props to the artists who’ve created a fun place to explore.

My 80s kid at heart did appreciate that there was a lot of space for free play, climbing, exploring.

But… There were WAY too many people in the facility. My husband commented that this may have been where Covid originated.   I understand that they are making $20-30 per person, so packing them in makes more money. But limiting the number of people would increase the quality of the experience so much more.

Gift shop idea- sell headphones or ear plugs!!!

It felt like half of the facility was food places, gift shops, and kiosks where you can spend more money.

There appears to be plenty of space in the building that isn’t being used. I’d consider visiting again if they open up new spaces to explore.  Otherwise, I most likely won’t return.

Took a 3yo and a 14yo, we ended up spending about 3hours here.  We had so much fun exploring, around literally every turn, corner, nook, and cranny.  Definitely want to return when my toddler is a little older, as I didn't feel safe letting them explore some of the smaller and darker areas.  Some sections seemed a little less tended to than others, but overall things were neat and appeared clean.

City Museum is awesome! I have been visiting it since 2005. It is still as fun as I have gotten older although a little rougher on the knees. The kids always have a wonderful time. You can spend a few hours or an entire day. The rotating exhibits keep things new and interesting. I highly recommend a visit if you are in St. Louis.

properties.adr_address: 5700 Lindell Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63112-0040, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Free historical museum with a focus on the state along with general American & Western themes.

properties.formatted_address: 5700 Lindell Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63112, USA
properties.name: Missouri History Museum

reviews.text: Today was my first time visiting and I can honestly say it’s a great experience! It’s called the Missouri History Museum but there is a big emphasis on St. Louis’ part in history. They have a new exhibit called St. Louis sound which narrates and show cases clothing, iconic figures, victories, and struggles of African Americans during the early 1900’s. What I love about each exhibit is that they are not only interactive but they are accessible to those who are hearing and visually impaired. You can have the exhibits described to you but scanning a QR code on your phone. The new St. Louis sound also has a really neat feature that allows you to listen to music throughout the ages as you walk through the exhibit to give it a more interactive feel. Some of the interactive stations were temporarily unavailable due to COVID and masks are required regardless of vaccination status. The museum was very clean and it was obvious the staff were taking measures to keep visitors safe. The other guests were courteous and mindful and it was quiet enough to enjoy and feel like you were the only one walking through. This is such a fun and educational experience and I recommend it to everyone!

A good museum to spend day to explore history that provided a lot of solid information. I thought it was well laid out and the paths were easy to follow. It really gave a strong flavor of what life was like in MO over the many years of development. I especially liked the exhibit on the 1904 Worlds Fair that explained the development of the area (which from the Art Museum, you can get a great view and imagine what it looked like in 1904. I did feel like I was getting a lot more "St. Louis" history than general MO history and would have liked to see an exhibit or some explanation of the Missouri Compromise as I didn't find one mention of that legislation which was pivotal in the years following the compromise and ultimately leading to where our country is today.

First the good part, it's free and there is free parking! As far as museums go though, it wasn't curated very well. Who ever writes their display plaques has a very negative view and they interject racism into everything. I get that it needs talked about on some displays, but it was put into almost every single information plaque and it was always in a negative light. Not let's learn from the past and move on, rather bitter and let's hold onto the divisions.
We have visited lots of history museums and we're looking forward to learning some state history, instead it was mostly just St. Louis history. Almost all the interactive displays were closed, maybe two out of fifty were open still. Every fifth or sixth display was empty or missing the display item. Not sure why they need to have so much of the items out.
The music section was interesting and informative, but you have to have a phone app to listen to the music. Not really inclusive to people who might not have good phones or the app. It would have been nice to just have some of the bands playing.
The World Fair section was interesting and well done. Probably our favorite section.
The new section is a "pride" section and wasn't open, so not sure how it will be.
The staff wasn't very friendly, except the gift shop worker when it was close to closing time. The gift shop was extensive and expensive.
Out of all the museums in Forrest Park, this was the least impressive. They need a new curator to change the direction of the museum.
It was free though and still had some educational opportunities for all ages. I would have given them three stars if the interactive displays weren't all closed.

I love going to museums and seeing history preserved 🏛 The Missouri History Museum didn't disappoint. With all the historical artifacts and St Louis preservation facts this place is great. Spent a few hours reading and viewing, a few interactive displays and a small refreshments Cafe on the second floor. Definitely a place to take the family and brush up on some local Missouri history 🛶⛴️

The great exhibits in this place really tell the story of our rich local heritage and how some of it made an impact on the mid-west and how our heritage influences on a global scale. And the best part is its free. My kids love this place.

properties.adr_address: 11 N 4th St, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Free National Park Service museum with exhibits on the history of the West, including Lewis & Clark.

properties.formatted_address: 11 N 4th St, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.name: Museum of Westward Expansion

reviews.text:
Wonderful experience. The views were terrific and the museum informative. The inside of the tram was tight, but an enjoyable ride. The gift shop has many options for souvenirs.

Its just cool. Thats really the bottom line. Its the signature thing to do in St. Louis, it almost define the city itself! Its a must do. Jaw-dropping brilliant feet of engineering .From the thrilling views from the top of arc to the bottom and amazing stories, a visit to the Gateway Arch is an experience that never fails to inspire.

From the thrilling views to the amazing stories, a visit to the Gateway Arch is an experience that never fails to inspire. Whether you have a few hours or a full day, you’ll find activities to please every member of your party. Attractions include the Tram Ride to the Top of the Gateway Arch, the Museum at the Gateway Arch (opened July 3, 2018), a documentary film about the construction of the Arch, shopping at The Arch Store, a new Arch Cafe, and cruises aboard the Riverboats at the Gateway Arch. Tickets sell out early and often - advance purchase strongly recommended. Closed Thanksgiving, Christmas Day and New Year's Day.

A nearly unknown museum, glad we poked around and found it.

Add understanding to all the events that occurred right here in this area.

Beautiful building and everything was presented so well.

Highly recommend!

Hosted in the Old Courthouse of Saint Louis, it offers comprehensive information on the origin of the city and on its function as gateway to the Western regions of the USA through the 19th century. Slavery of African people and their fight for freedom is also very well discussed. Highly recommended and definitely worth the half day visit.

When I entered the building I asked if it was the Museum of Westward Expansion because I did not see a sign with that name. The park service staff told me it used to be under the Arch and it closed but some of the exhibits are now in the Old Court House, which is the building marked in Google maps (March 2017). I was confused but I toured the museum anyway. I learned so much about the St. Louis area, Dred Scott and westward trade and exploration. Some of the exhibits are a little old and I did not see newer, updated interactive exhibits for kids, but I still encourage families to take children. All the kids I saw were having fun! I enjoyed the exhibits and the architecture.  I'm not sure if this location is mislabeled on Google or something. I'm still confused about where I spent my afternoon but I had fun!
Wonderful history.  Nice place to visit.  Make sure to check which days they run everything before toy go.

properties.adr_address: 1508 Locust St, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Restored 19th-century home displaying period furnishings, paintings & the family's personal effects.

properties.formatted_address: 1508 Locust St, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA
properties.name: Campbell House Museum

reviews.text: Beautiful Victorian Home. Tour Guide Ginger was an amazing historian of the home and have a wonderfully nice personality. The home is well kept and clean, very much worth $10 dollars per person. Our tour last around an hour long as well. I contributed $50 to keep the home in tip top shape.
Great little museum preserving a little chapter of St Louis history.  An Intern gave the tour and did a good job

Lovely restored and preserved Victorian home! Honestly the most beautiful historic home I've toured. Our tour guide was very knowledgeable and presented in details about the house! A must see in st Louis!!

This is an unbelievable experience. The house, story, and furnishings are all restored and so unique. If visiting St. Louis, this should be a top attraction, along with the Arch, Zoo, Soulard, Lafayette Square, Forest Park, and Anheuser Busch Brewery. The tour is very reasonably priced and worth every penny.

This tour gave us a true picture of a Victorian home, ESPECIALLY since everything in the house is original AND there are so many well-preserved photos!
Dennis, our docent is both passionate & extremely knowledgeable about all aspects of the property.

properties.adr_address: 1 Fine Arts Dr, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Grand beaux arts building & modern extension housing over 30,000 works of art, with free admission.

properties.formatted_address: 1 Fine Arts Dr, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.name: Saint Louis Art Museum

reviews.text: My wife and I went to the Saints Louis Art Museum on a Saturday a little before noon. It wasn't very crowded at all. It definitely feels more like an art museum than an art gallery which I think I prefer. Lots of art ranging from paintings, pottery to medieval armor and mummies. I had read it would take about 2 1/2 hours to see everything, well after 5 hours, we still hadn't seen everything. This place has a lot to see, and if you take your time it can take up a whole day. We really enjoyed our visit here and will definitely be coming back in the future.

First-class free museum (except for special exhibits) with something for everyone. Classics or modern, painting or sculpture, this museum has it. We were impressed with the very good, helpful explanations for each piece. Lots of free parking and a stunning view over Forest Park. This is definitely a sampling of "everything art." - From classic paintings, famous artists, and cultural art ranging from a variety of American Indian cultures to Egyptian to the various art revolutions, and even modern art, this museum has it all. Various furniture pieces and fully furnished rooms of historical times give the viewer a sense of what a room would look like during the period of time and location portrayed. It has so much, I could see visiting and focusing on particular aspects and needing to come back multiple times to appreciate all that they have to offer.

Like so many other amazing stops in St Louis, the Art Museum is free. 3 levels of art collections from every culture and genre. Everything you can imagine. Also has a gift shop and a small cafe. One really unique thing they have is they've taken the inside of some historic American homes and relocated them here inside the museum. Love visiting here. Outside there is the view on Art Hill, overlooking the water and fountains. Its very nice and a lot of people had professional photos done outside of the museum. Parking around this area is the biggest challenge. Depending on when you go there might be an open spot in the free lot. Otherwise, there is the museum garage that costs, or you can street park, but expect to walk a few blocks. Don't try and park in illegal spaces. The park rangers are out in force.

Free admission!
A wide range of collections!
Super nice organized in different categories and themes.
Loved the landscape design outside the museum: open view of the pond on a hill in the big park!! What a great treasure and gift that the city of St. Louis sends to the visitors. It greatly changed my preconception of St. Louis as a city in the Midwest. Such a great city with so many to offer!

We came on a very cold day so I did not get to explore all of the beautiful park but just this short visit has me excited to come back soon. The textiles exhibit was interesting and well worth checking out (especially on Fridays since ticketed sections are free). It looks like they're expanding the arms and armor exhibit which is pretty exciting. The cafe food was really good too! Looking forward to my next trip.

properties.adr_address: 5050 Oakland Ave, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Planetarium at the St. Louis Science Center since 1963, with live star shows & interactive exhibits.

properties.formatted_address: 5050 Oakland Ave, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.name: Saint Louis Science Center

reviews.text: The science center is a wonderful experience! Our 5 year old had a fantastic time. There are three floors of exhibits as well as two gift shops,  a theater, planetarium, and small area for concessions. General admission is free but the shows, planetarium, and some other things do cost, as well as parking is $10 if you're not a member. We visited on a Saturday morning. There was no wait to get in, nor to buy tickets to anything, but the whole place was quite busy. Overall, we had a great time and would recommend visiting.

Pretty neat place for you to bring your family. It's a great place to learn about science and see how some common things work. It's free to enter, but some attractions require you to purchase tickets. There's free street parking if you're willing to walk a couple minutes. You can also park at forest park and walk through from the planetarium side.

Another great, free gem for our city. So many exhibits and areas to explore. Throughout the many floors, you can learn about all things science! There are Hands-On activities and artifacts as well as demonstrations and shows. It's a great place to spend the day with kids of all ages. There are other activities for additional cost such as toddler areas, educational movies and interactive exhibits. The video game exhibit on the bottom floor was a little lacking since there were many things that were out of service. The kids always love exploring the dinosaur area and seeing some fossils and geological finds from our area is always cool. We usually park over at the planetarium and walk across the bridge to view the cars driving below but the parking lot has been closed for some time. Unfortunately, the only other parking besides street parking which is 3 hours, is the science Center lot which costs $12. If you purchase a movie ticket you only pay $6 for parking. They offer military discount for service members on several paid offerings. There are concessions and drinking fountains throughout. We really enjoyed the vault area which can be found on the planetarium side of the bridge. Definitely check it out if you're in the St Louis area. We are grateful for this great addition to the city!

Amazing place for you to explore the wonders of science . Visited this with a 6 years and 10 years old, they absolutely loved it. Would definitely recommend this place. The planetarium entrance is closed. So you will have to either find street side parking or pay and park in the science center parking lot , which costs around $12.  The paid parking lot has many fuel efficient parking spaces and 2 electric car charging station.

We had so much fun at the St. Louis Science Center. It’s probably the best science center I’ve ever been to and it’s awesome that it’s free. We will definitely go again. I only expected to spend maybe 2 hours but we spent 3 and only left then because we had other reservations. You could easily spend 4+ hours. The video game display could use a little attention though many of those items did not work as intended.

properties.adr_address: 634 S Broadway, St. Louis, MO 63102-1613, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Tours of the Victorian boyhood home of Dred Scott's attorney along with antique toy exhibits & shop.

properties.formatted_address: 634 S Broadway, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.name: The Field House Museum

reviews.text: Went to see the Annie Malone exhibit at the Eugene Field House. Both of them are St. Louis treasures. Kudos to Linda Nance for preserving this history of a remarkable woman. Glad we saw it.

Among the numerous historic homes in town, this is unremarkable by comparison. The third floor was was under repair so fully 1/3 of the home is unavailable. The home is attached to a toy museum, as Mr. Field was a noted collector -- and even this collection is modest and not outstanding. The fee was excessive for the tour. In brief, other historic St. Louis homes are much better maintained or have better collections.
Nice little museum. Dressed for the Christmas season now. Very nice.

The birthplace of Eugene Fields (1850) known as "The Children's Poet".  3 story building contains several pieces of furnishings of that time.  Eugene's Father Roswell was a lawyer that represented Dred and Harriett Scott in their quest for freedom by utilizing a unique legal challenge. It is located just South of Busch Stadium on South Broadway.  Daily  tours are available Wednesday through Sunday.

Just spent a delightful morning touring the Eugene Fields House and loved every minute. The guided part of the tour was wonderful and it is very apparent the research and great care that has gone into this marvelous museum. The furnishings just gorgeous and many of them original to the home and Fields family. The quilt exhibit from the 1800's was amazing. It is well worth your time to visit this historic home, Learn abaut Eugene Fields and his family and meet the staff who are warm, welcoming, and well informed. Wonderful experience and I plan on taking my grandchildren there next visit.

properties.adr_address: 2505 St Louis Ave, St. Louis, MO 63106-2324, USA
properties.formatted_address: 2505 St Louis Ave, St. Louis, MO 63106, USA
properties.name: Griot Museum of Black History

reviews.text: A very interesting museum with unique exhibits that are a mix of entertaining and moving. The Josephine Baker exhibit is beautiful. While the exhibit about the slave trade and the middle passage was heart wrenching and thought provoking. Definitely one of the more unique attractions of St Louis.
The wax exhibit was excellent.the story telling was very informative I learn a lot of history there I will go back again if I am ever in town. Unfortunately we are not aloud to take pictures.

The content and education were very detailed and educational. From a servicing standpoint (which I'm big on) the brunette at the front desk didn't seem to be the best for the job. Lazy and lack of empathy is what I felt from her. Also their website needs to clarify that reservations are required as many visitors had no clue.
Took the kids for a dose of black history. It was eye opening for them. Great experience, bought a cook homemade bracelet.

My two 6yr olds were bored and couldn't quite understand ( could be a little more interactive).  The three yr old was afraid and only wanted to color in the hallway.  But my 9yr old found it Very Interesting.  I even Learned a few things while reading to Them 😊.

properties.adr_address: 3750 Washington Ave, St. Louis, MO 63108, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Venerable institution featuring modern art exhibits, as well as related educational programs.

properties.formatted_address: 3750 Washington Ave, St. Louis, MO 63108, USA
properties.name: Contemporary Art Museum St. Louis

reviews.text: A vibrant midtown museum with rotating exhibition of amazing artists from world over. It’s all free and ample parking available around the building. The large space with some video- audio displays are very interesting touch. A small cafe with a nice outdoor space to have a cup of cappuccino!

Saint Louis is a city that.is lucky to have such a vibrant arts scene, and one of the crowning jewels.is the Contemporary Art Museum.  Tucked away in Grand Center, the CAM is FREE to all guests and provides several galleries of cutting-edge, thoughtful, and thought-provoking work.  Stop by often and immerse yourself in their exhibits and then come back again to find something new.

Didn’t know what to expect coming here. Museum is free. Upstairs they have art from High school kids talking about equity & equality. Downstairs there’s more adult art from when we visited. Very abstract, thought provoking, graphic. Don’t bring kids to the downstairs there is nudity. Very fun place.

Profetic 2nd floor installment done to promote artwork for equity was magnificent beyond words. Its shine was diminished due to the main exhibitions cacophony of insanity.

For better accessibility and immersion in various experiences, a start and stop button per video station would have allowed people to start the videos' Journey at any time. Unless it was the artist intent to overwhelm people with sensory issues, glad I brought my headphones, I believe they would like their art respected as individual pieces instead of Orchestra of Madness.

Sustainability and energy wise? I would be curious to know their data on how many people visit throughout the week. I was there most of the afternoon on a weekday and felt like the only 1 at times. Yet, videos play on auto loop. As some of the videos were longer, I also had to wait quite a while to fully enjoy each of the pieces. More often than not, people would walk by without stopping for long.

Conversations about gender are person specific and not easily understood without starting from the intended artists' beginning. For this reason, it was disappointing for me on various levels.
Stopped by here on a whim and was glad we did. My kids loved the displays and the area upstairs where they could make their own art. I'm sure we will be returning at some point in time.

properties.adr_address: 1 Brookings Dr, St. Louis, MO 63130, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Teaching museum with an art collection focused on European & American works from the 1800s to now.

properties.formatted_address: 1 Brookings Dr, St. Louis, MO 63130, USA
properties.name: Mildred Lane Kemper Art Museum

reviews.text: Nicely curated permanent collections including artists such as Pollock, Warhol, and Max Ernst, plus interesting temporary exhibits. It is a small museum but worth a visit, especially since it's free! Check out the art sculptures/exhibits outside as well.

My partner and I were in St. Louis for the day, and were excited to visit some cool places. Unfortunately most things are closed on Mondays, so we thought we settled for a less impressive art gallery. We were very sorely mistaken however, and the Kemper Art Museum vastly exceeded our expectations. They had an impressively robust permanent collection and timely exhibits, mostly curated and created by Washington University students. I am excited to go back!

What a carefully curated collection of unexpected gems. I found my favorite Max Ernst today, an excellent non-drip Jackson Pollock, a delicious Frederic Church, and a number of paintings and installations by contemporary artists I didn't know, but will start to follow. Of note is the work by Chitra Ganesh. Do not miss her short surrealist/multiversal animated films in the basement.

I saw a number of reviews complaining about staff. I can only saw the front desk and security staff were friendly and professional. Ignore the negative reviews.

Parking in East End Garage was remarkably straightforward and a reasonable series of steps (didn't check for an elevator but I would guess one is available) and short walk from the museum's entrance.
Awesome exhibit on contemporary art. The Katharina Grosse exhibition was probably my favorite part, although there's something for everyone...
Quite an excellent museum right there at Washington University in St Louis.  World class art and artists are here...a beautiful structure and we'll curated...a place to see.  Loved the Ai Exhibit

properties.adr_address: 1315 Chestnut St, St. Louis, MO 63103-2317, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Edifice honoring local soldiers, featuring military-related historical exhibits.

properties.formatted_address: 1315 Chestnut St, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA
properties.name: Soldiers Memorial Military Museum

reviews.text: A little bit of history in downtown St Louis.  Very cool building.  I love the architecture on the outside.  There are two sides to the museum.  One side is WW1 and the other side is WW2.  If you are into history, this is something worth checking out if you are in the area.

The Military Museum is very well organized, with a lot of information about the wars Missourians and the nation have fought. There is just enough information to keep it interesting and to be able to read it all within an hour and a half without being too much that it gets a bit dull. I highly recommend as it is a beautiful and well established museum.

This was a humbly and emotional experience expesically given what is going on in Ukraine. All American War tributes are displayed even the American Revolutionary war all the way up to America's last war. Even includes Cold War information. I suggest going along so you can really have an intrinsic emotional experience to take it all in.But if in a group that's good too because you can then all discuss your individual feelings afterwards. I never served in the military but I have so much more respect and adoration for those that fought for my freedom! Very emotional experience!
What a wonderful and humbling museum experience. It's small but mighty in the quality of what you're seeing. A great way to learn about the selfless sacrifice of so many from St. Louis.
Beautiful memorial. Very informative and great to see all of the memorabilia. Was glad to have visited it memorial day weekend and if we're ever back in town, will stop by again for sure.

properties.adr_address: 3716 Washington Ave, St. Louis, MO 63108-3612, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Contemporary home to a small art collection & host of rotating art exhibits, with limited hours.

properties.formatted_address: 3716 Washington Ave, St. Louis, MO 63108, USA
properties.name: Pulitzer Arts Foundation

reviews.text:
Pulitzer arts foundation is one of my top 5 museums in the states. This museum reminds me of Dia:Beacon. The architecture is simple and modern. Love the art selection there. It’s a free museum but the quality is amazing. Their artists introduction card printing is super high quality and you can take it home if you want. Also, not sure if this is always a thing but you can also write a postcard there and they will send it to the address you put for free as well.

They are holding their first “interactive” exhibit there and it was very fun! A lot of arts you can play around and it’s very inspiring!

A crown jewel of STL midtown Grand Art Center. The building itself is a exceptional craftsmanship by Japanese architect Tadao Ando with unpolished exterior and interior walls, natural light coming from the roof and a serene bamboo garden and the peaceful water court. The Blue-Black art by Elssworth Kelly is the center point of the expansive main floor. The mammoth spiral weathered steel work by Richard Serra is one of a kind! With regular changing exhibits, public lectures and other events this place can always be  something to look forward to visit again and again!   The view of some of the surrounding old buildings can be appreciated from the courtyard. Across the street from the main building is a small Park-like urban green space.

Came to the Pulitzer Arts Foundation specifically to see the exhibition by Barbara chase Riboud and was not disappointed. Lovely museum space. Not a lot of people around so had a good chance to spend time with the artwork without distractions. The staff was uniformly helpful.

I actually own a piece by Barbara Chase Riboud and I brought it with me to the museum to show the staff.  It is an etching that Chase Riboud did while she was still a student at Temple University’s Tyler School of Art  in Philadlphia.  It is undated but I would guess it was done in 1958 of 1959 while she was still a student. (Chase Riboud earned her Bachelor of Fine Arts from Tyler in 1959.)

After college, Chase moved to Paris, France, where she established a studio and married photographer Marc Riboud on December 21, 1961. The etching is signed "Barbara Chase" demonstrating the she was unmarried at the time she signed it.

Unfortunately I came on a Saturday and none of the curators was available to discuss the etching. Maybe next time I am in St. Louis I willcall ahead.

Small but ver interesting musuem! They have a great layout and explanations about their pieces and the artists. Only took some stars because they forced me to take my backpack off which was fine but then I noticed I was the only one they asked as there were various other people with them so they obviousky picked me out for some "reason"
Lovely campus, plenty of parking, free admission! What more could you want? I appreciate the thoughtfully-curated exhibits.

properties.adr_address: 1 Federal Reserve Bank Plaza, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.formatted_address: 1 Federal Reserve Bank Plaza, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.name: Inside the Economy Museum at the Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis

html_attributions: Inside the Economy Museum at the Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis
Inside the Economy Museum at the Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis
Inside the Economy Museum at the Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis

reviews.text: I always like visit Federal Reserve Bank museum in other States. Free to come. Recommended and buy some souvenirs from FRB gift shop inside. Don’t forget to visit this place when you’re in St Louis area.
Awesome interactive place. So many great videos and things for kids to do. Totally worth stopping in for a couple hours. Even free souvenirs at the end.
Interesting.... I had to wear a mask because I didn't have my updated vaccine booster information. Not a big deal.

Adults had to show photo ID (currently no mask/vaccine requirements) and the check in process  took a few minutes. The museum was great! Content seems aimed at teenage learners but there was more than enough for our 9 year old to interact with.  It was a valuable learning experience presented in a way that really stuck with him.

No longer need proof of vaccination or masks. We visited the Economy Museum without many expectations but my sons (14, 11, 8) all really enjoyed the experience. Many interactive exhibits and an area to try your hand at trading on the stock market. We had the opportunity to try and lift a gold brick, learn about and see ancient currency, identify fake currency, and view the currency of many other countries. My husband was impressed with the relevancy of the information and how up to date the information was. A bonus is the bag of shredded cash all guests are allowed to take. Overall, a nice experience. Middle school and up is the target audience but there was plenty of stuff to keep the 8 year old entertained. Worth a visit! Spent about 1.5 hours there.

properties.vicinity: 1 Federal Reserve Bank Plaza, St. Louis

properties.adr_address: 4746 Gravois Ave, St. Louis, MO 63116-2437, USA
properties.formatted_address: 4746 Gravois Ave, St. Louis, MO 63116, USA
properties.name: Miniature Museum of Greater St. Louis

reviews.text:
This museum was outstanding!  Soooo much to see!  Dollhouses of all types and scales. It kind of boggles the mind, and honestly, there was so much to see that my eyes were legitimately tired when we were done.

There is a small $7/person entry fee. They do have a $1 coupon on their website.  We were only able to spend a little over an hour at the location. We could have been there at least 2 hours.

The museum includes a dollhouse store. (No entry fee to shop the store).

The only shortcomings: The museum would be hard for a person with limited mobility to explore. And I’m not sure they’d be able to access the second floor at all.  Nearly all of the displays are lighted, but a few lights didn’t work.

I bought admission from a Groupon ad. I have a small dollhouse and was interested in seeing what this place had to offer.  The experience was even better than I had imagined!  There was so much to look at & so many interesting displays.  I especially enjoyed the miniature of Bevo Mill right across the street!  They also have a gift shop where I could buy quality dollhouse items.  It’s hard to find decent furniture anywhere.  I was so thrilled that I immediately bought a membership!

This place has so many miniatures with great  details. It was great to take the time and peer in and notice all the great craftsmanship. There’s miniatures of the Old Cathedral and a wide variety of styles across two floors. It’s a hidden gem for the city.

In my husband's words, "this place is surprisingly awesome." I found it through Atlas Obscura, and with my daughter's love of all things tiny (mini brands and LOL surprise), I thought she might like checking it out. She loved it so much she is now considering a new hobby (oops).

I highly recommend a visit if you are at all interested in miniatures, museums, and detailed crafting. The ladies working there are super sweet and friendly, finding the miniature chess table with pieces my daughter HAD to have. Long after the absurdly small chess pieces are gone for good, we'll still have some pretty amazing memories and will likely make a return trip. They do have a Groupon right now, too!
Very interesting especially to see the details. Not sure how many our on display but we spent oe to 2 hours. Well worth the admission.

properties.adr_address: 615 Washington Ave, St. Louis, MO 63101, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Museum featuring interactive exhibits focused on the history of blues music, plus a theater.

properties.formatted_address: 615 Washington Ave, St. Louis, MO 63101, USA
properties.name: National Blues Museum

reviews.text:
Incredible way to spend an afternoon! Give yourself more than an hour so you can read and listen all you like.

So much history. Great tunes. Interactive exhibits. Reminders of musicians you've loved and forgotten over the years.

The museum is taking COVID precautions and you're asked to book tickets starting at a particular time and to wear a face mask.

The employee at the front desk was so genuinely sweet and really brightened my day.

Small but so well done! So many interactive exhibits you can spend hours just playing around with those. Several great films to watch. Great displays and the staff were wonderful, over the top friendly! I was very surprised with the gift shop. Finding a gift shop that is not overpriced is a shock these days. If you are in the city make the time to stop in. Totally worth the time. Plus the location is great for food and drinks afterwards.

I had a blast . Ms Debra @ the front desk really looked out for us. She allow my friend and I to bring our loaded Bicycles inside so we could enjoy the museum. Very kinda staff and very lovely experience. Will go back again in the future for some refreshing. ✌🏽

I was there during museum hours.  It is an interactive museum with the history of blues from Africa to current times and it’s impact on different genres of music .   You can even write and mix your own blues song thanks to Jack White.

We were in town for the weekend and stopped into the Museum spur of the moment. It was $15/adult ticket. There was no wait. First thing we did was use the women's restroom. Most of the soap dispensers were out of soap and the restroom was quite messy considering at the time we entered we were the only 2 guests. The actual museum expected was nice. It is a self-guided tour. It takes you through the different decades of jazz music from the Jim Crow era to current day. There are also some hands on exhibits to try. Definitely worth a visit at least once.

properties.adr_address: 3700 W Pine Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63108, USA
properties.formatted_address: 3700 W Pine Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63108, USA
properties.name: Museum of Contemporary Religious Art

reviews.text: Was an interesting and fun experience

There are few places like this in the world. You can tell that the curator has great depth, and is always able to put together something extraordinary, profound, and tremendously enjoyable. I've seen people there last on the floor smiling for an exhibit of silver clouds. I've seem people tear up at the suffering conveyed by some pieces, and I've seen people slow down to the point of connecting with God. I can't recommend this gem highly enough. Please ask for a tour.

Dim lighting lends to a sense of spiritual experience; exiting into the harsh sunlight felt like emerging into another world altogether. I do wish the exhibits were lit somewhat better themselves, however. A small space, though the balcony exhibits were closed, I went through in less than an hour.
I found myself deeply moved by the visiting photography display by Tom Kiefer. Well worth checking out.
I expected to find a greater diversity of religions represented, such as Judaism, Islam, and Hinduism. Not much other than Catholicism on display, but it is a small, free museum on a college campus and there's only so much they can afford.
Quite a unique place. Very rich history to the art and a great collection
Closed. No warning. Spent all afternoon trying to find it. Bah humbug.

properties.adr_address: 700 Clark Ave, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Located in Ballpark Village, this self-guided museum showcases a variety of Cardinals memorabilia.

properties.formatted_address: 700 Clark Ave, St. Louis, MO 63102, USA
properties.name: St. Louis Cardinals Hall of Fame and Museum

reviews.text: My family and I FINALLY visited over the weekend for the first time, and we were SO impressed! I’m not a St. Louis native, or even a big baseball fan (though I love going to the games, and the Cardinals have my full support), but I really enjoyed the museum quite a lot! It’s beautiful, pristinely clean and cared for, there’s a TON of things to see and read about, it’s very kid-friendly, and I’d actually enjoy going back! My husband, a St. Louis native and HUGE, lifelong Cardinals fan, held bats that were actually used by Stan and Ozzie, which was super cool; he even got to hold a couple of World Series rings. Our little one thoroughly enjoyed visiting as well, which was so great for us because my hubby got to take his time and really take everything in. Regardless of your status as a baseball fan, this is a really cool stop to add to your “things to do in the Lou” list. I took tons of photos, and wanted to give y’all a little peek inside the place.

If you’re into the Redbirds, the St. Louis Cardinals Hall of Fame is a must-visit location, with a trove of baseball treasures. Fans of all ages will enjoy touring the exhibits and learning the city’s deep sports history.
Phenomenal museum – maybe second only to Cooperstown as far as baseball museums go! Lots of exhibits and artifacts, including the ability to hold game-used items like Stan Musial’s bat.

These picture don’t even scratch the surface of this museum. We did the museum as a a part of our tour of Busch Stadium and I’m glad we took the time to go over and check it out. We had our 3 and 1 year old with us and they had a blast. My husband loves the cardinals and he was much more excited than them lol. It was pretty cool to see the history and there were so many interactive things to keep everyone engaged.

The museum begins with a video that is worth watching and our kids actually sat through it. Anyone would enjoy it but if you’re a cardinals fan you’ll be in cardinals history heaven.

Definitely go. And it wasn’t crowded at all when we went.

Beautifully displayed trophies, uniforms, equipment and photos explain the 130+ year history of a great baseball franchise. It is a wonderful walk down memory lane for a true Cardinal fan. Learned new facts too.

properties.adr_address: St. Louis, MO 63113, USA
properties.formatted_address: St. Louis, MO 63113, USA
properties.name: Museum at the Gateway Arch

reviews.text: Wow, what a great museum. It was engaging and really well thought out. Lots of interactive elements to attract all ages. It's not a boring museum at all. Plus, it's free to visit. My family of 4 really enjoyed our time here and learned a good deal about the history of this area. I'd highly recommend a visit.

Visited on a Thursday morning. We got tickets to ride up to the top of the arch, and visited the museum while waiting. I highly recommend, as it’s a national park masks are required inside. We had no wait. Very informative and fun. Had interactive sections. They only thing I didn’t like how pricey the cafe was. The bathrooms were clean.

Wonderful experience. The views were terrific and the museum informative. The inside of the tram was tight, but an enjoyable ride. The gift shop has many options for souvenirs.

Its just cool. Thats really the bottom line. Its the signature thing to do in St. Louis, it almost define the city itself! Its a must do. Jaw-dropping brilliant feet of engineering .From the thrilling views from the top of arc to the bottom and amazing stories, a visit to the Gateway Arch is an experience that never fails to inspire.

From the thrilling views to the amazing stories, a visit to the Gateway Arch is an experience that never fails to inspire. Whether you have a few hours or a full day, you’ll find activities to please every member of your party. Attractions include the Tram Ride to the Top of the Gateway Arch, the Museum at the Gateway Arch (opened July 3, 2018), a documentary film about the construction of the Arch, shopping at The Arch Store, a new Arch Cafe, and cruises aboard the Riverboats at the Gateway Arch. Tickets sell out early and often - advance purchase strongly recommended. Closed Thanksgiving, Christmas Day and New Year's Day.

The arch museum is amazing with so much history ready to learn in wonderful visual displays. Come early so you can spend more time in the museum. My kids loved the Junior Ranger program. It helped us all to learn and take away more from our visit. The arch tour is great. Don't miss out!

Absolutely fascinating. This free museum is better than several museums I've been to where I had to pay exorbitant amounts of money to enter. So many interesting exhibits and artifacts. I love how each section represents a different time period, going back to the 1700s all the way to today. I wish I had more time to really absorb everything. You could easily spend 2+ hours if you read through the text and watched the interactive videos. I especially appreciated learning more about Native American history and how the museum didn't sugarcoat the hard stuff.

properties.adr_address: 3408 Locust St, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Displaying a collection of rare & vintage European motorcycles, with paid guided tours available.

properties.formatted_address: 3408 Locust St, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA
properties.name: The Moto Museum

reviews.text: As a motorcycle enthusiast, I absolutely loved this museum. There's a wonderful variety of motorcycles from all throughout the 20th and 21st centuries from several countries. The founder and collector, Mr. Steve Smith, did a great job with this facility and I enjoyed the information on the placards explaining the history of the bike and story of how Mr. Smith acquired the bike.

We had our wedding here. Best decision we made! From our first tour, we were sold. Not only was the space cool and unique, the event team was by far the best, most personable and most accommodating we met. Our coordinator Steve sealed the deal and made our event perfect! Anything we asked, he was accommodating to. Colleen was also fabulous, couldn't have asked for a better team. Day of, our wedding was amazing, to see how they transformed the space was breathtaking, they truly brought my (our) vision to life. While the space is obviously filled with motorcycles, it's amazing how they were able to transform the space to make it what we wanted. Everyone raved about the food and the event staff made sure everything was perfect and attended to all our needs the night of...no matter the request. Seriously would recommend this space and team to anyone
Loved the primarily pre-1975 European motorcycle collection! Worth a visit especially since the museum is free.
This is well worth a visit, especially if you  love vintage, rare motorcycles.

Finally got the Bluetooth module installed on my Triumph Speed Triple and Moto Europa was awesome about getting the software update done. Great shop! Thank you for sharing the info about the update and how it's done.

properties.adr_address: 3673 W Pine Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Late-19th-century sandstone mansion with an accompanying collection of fine & decorative art.

properties.formatted_address: 3673 W Pine Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA
properties.name: Samuel Cupples House

reviews.text:
This is a lovely place on the SLU campus! The house is beautiful and restored very well. They provide a very informative self-guide binder that I found easy to follow. The student who was working there (Hi Selam!) very helpfully and cheerfully found the answer to an obscure question I had. It was a great way to spend a couple of hours. And it's air conditioned which is important in July 2022!

A few notes: As of 7/8/2022, there is construction going on and you can not get in through the front. If you walk around to the back, there is an entrance there.
While there is a wheelchair lift that will get you into the house, there is no access to the second or third floors other than the stairs.

Samuel Cupples House is a blast from the past…LITERALLY! This house has been standing since 1890. It is located on Saint Louis University Campus. There is meter parking on Lindell by St. Francis Church. The restored house is beautiful. They have a folder of it history that you can grab because it’s a self-guided tour. You can walk around yourself and take your time looking at everything. Pictures are allowed WITHOUT flash. It’s open Tuesday- Saturday, 11am to 4pm. I went there on a friday around 11am and it was empty. It was a little creepy being there by myself. It was nice to see how wealthy people lived in the past. The rooms, decor, walls, fireplaces were exquisite. Such a lovely house. Oh and it’s free.

Wow! Found this place looking for a historic house to visit and it didn't disappoint. Park in the parking garage towards the side and walk straight into campus and it's only about 5 mins. Gorgeous stained glass and collectables in this three story home. Worth the visit especially around the Holidays

An interesting mansion with many artistic features including interesting hand carved wood working and tile mosaic featuring many interesting articles from the 1850s to 1900s

Samuel cupples had made his fortune by selling wood furniture and later on selling a wide variety of general every-day use items

Samuel cupples had a fondness for glass sculptures and many more had been donated to their collection that is on display at the house

The self-guided tour is free

Extraordinarily well maintained home rich in St. Louis history. The home is lavishly appointed with period furniture and fixtures. Of all the historic homes in town, I believe this is the best. And gravy for the goose, there is no admission charged.

properties.adr_address: 4652 Maryland Ave #1, St. Louis, MO 63108-1913, USA

editorial_summary.overview: This museum in a historic building explores the game of chess, with exhibits, tours & a gift shop.

properties.formatted_address: 4652 Maryland Ave #1, St. Louis, MO 63108, USA
properties.name: World Chess Hall of Fame

reviews.text: Fun, free and entertaining. If you're a chess nerd like mine this place is enjoyable and informative. But even for the casual player, the giant chessboard and "World's biggest chess piece" are worth a stop by. You can grab you a free poster and if you participate in the scavenger hunt then they offer small prizes! My kids really loved the scavenger hunt and battled it out on the board! The wife had to drag them (and me) off of it when it was time to go. Great place to grab a coffee (right next door) and play a game! It costs nothing, but if you can drop a small donation at the front desk, that is not only a polite and easy way to say thank you, it also helps keep places like this running!

Amazing place, the only reason I left 1 star out is because when I got there at 6pm they just told me the museum closed but the gift shop was open. The place didn't close until 9pm that night but they shut down the main attraction 3 hours prior to the store closing?? Otherwise, the gift shop and front way is incredible with everything you'd want for a chess nut, and things even if you're not! The staff were accommodating saying they could also order the same items in store to be delivered to your address if you don't want to carry them around the city or are visiting from out of state. Some sets are the size of your leg, others are micro with collapsible/magnetic pieces, perfect for playing on the go. A whole bunch of accessories to keep you thinking about the game wherever you are from keyrings, bags, stress balls in the shape of your favorite pieces, candles, cards, and a ton of other knick-knacks. Last but not least, the location is ideal as the largest chess piece in the world rests just off the sidewalk of a beautifully lit avenue on the corner of a chess themed bar. You can play the game with your friends in or out of the store/bar too. A must see!

Really neat experience. It isn't everyday that you get to see a place devoted to the game of chess. I'm not sure how long it is running but the Mind Art Experience exhibit was a really interesting exhibit that I think we were lucky to have gotten a chance to see.

Very interesting if you like museums, chess, and/or art. A lot of really interesting chessboard and chess-inspired art pieces.  The world's largest chess piece is out front, and a board with knee-high but lightweight pieces, plus several standard tables. The STL chess club offices are across the street with more tables, and the museum has a nice gift shop inside. Also, it's free!

Sorry, I forgot to take pics in the museum (was fun, got distracted, lol) but these are from the gift shop.

Kids were off school today took a day trip as my son 10 & daughter 11  just got into chess club. Very unique place. Would have loved to play chess outside in the front but the snow stopped us... next time!

properties.adr_address: 3663 Lindell Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63108-3301, USA
properties.formatted_address: 3663 Lindell Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63108, USA
properties.name: The Saint Louis University Museum of Art

reviews.text: Something of a skeepy little museum, but definitely worth checking out.  First floor was a use of plastic which was interesting, maybe.  The second floor was the paintings.  The third floor was more historic religious artifacts, but also a lot devoted to Native American

The museum carries a mixed collection of artists, some quite notable (a Chagall, Kandinsky, Warhol, Lichtenstein), but they are few and none particularly notable. One full floor is dedicated to the Jesuits, for those interested in Catholic art and artifacts.

Very cool!  Lots of nice art on the second floor, an entire little museum of Jesuit missions on the third.  I'd go again if it wasn't for a seeming lack of free parking.  Really only was able to go because I was already on campus for something else.  If you're ever in the area, it's worth a visit!  Just pay attention to the hours.  I think it's open til 4 most days.  Really cool place!
Interesting historical building with art of all sorts, ranging from new and colorful to old religious artifacts

This is a very interesting art museum. I went with a group and we had a tour guide, she was absolutely fantastic! We talked more about the details and set up of galleries since we were all art teachers, the guide was more than happy to share all of the extra information. I believe there are 4 floors. One floor is all about SLU's history, another floor is about St. Louis and Missouri history, another has a lot of modern art from around the world, and the last one was blocked off at the time but I think it will have Asian art. I definitely recommend this to anyone especially if you love art!

properties.adr_address: 1100 Macklind Ave, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.formatted_address: 1100 Macklind Ave, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.name: HealthWorks! Kids' Museum St. Louis

reviews.text: Hello everyone to whom is reading this. The place we are talking about is something I wish I could  have had when I was a Child. This place is supper cool. I mean if you are looking for a good time and educational. This is a great place for family time. When u look at the pictures it does not do it justice and I can say enough about how great this place really is.  I know I will be letting everyone know about this place and highly recommend to everyone of all ages to come check this place out. Great work to the lady's that run this place and the employees willing to so what ever it takes to make sure the customers has a great time. Keep up the good work.

This was a pretty cool and educational visit. I have an almost three year old and she was pretty entertained by the big slide and the kitchen/foods area. I visited with several other moms and kids and a small presentation of food groups was put on by staff. Kids were asked to participate. The staff were friendly. No wow factor per say, but definitely worth a visit.
My 8 year old son has a great experience here. With added attractions this will be a very nice place to visit.

This venue was a great place for our girl scouts outing. I will definitely be booking for my child's birthday party. It's got an amazing body, a little marker, child size dentist and doctor office, they put a great show in the dental theater and the people are so polite and the environment is Beautiful and welcoming to little people.

Healthworks is a hidden gem! I didn’t know it existed until I need to kill some time after my son’s doctor appointment. It’s located across from St. Louis Community College. It has a ton of parking in the lot in front of the building. The staff is nice. Kids are free under 3 years old. $7 after they are 3 years old. Adults are $7 as well. There are so many things children can do and learn here. There is a light reaction game under the ribcage of the Giant man, there is slide that is the man’s leg. There is a doctor and dentist office, complete with the coats, and x-rays, etc. There is a market where they can shop for fruits and vegetables. My son had a blast running around! There was only two other kids there when I went on a friday afternoon at 3:30pm.

properties.adr_address: 5595 Grand Dr, St. Louis, MO 63112, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Opened in 1876, this 1,300-acre park includes 3 museums, a zoo, athletic fields & golf courses.

properties.formatted_address: 5595 Grand Dr, St. Louis, MO 63112, USA
properties.name: Forest Park

reviews.text: This park is amazing. The only parks I've been to that compare are Central Park and Golden Gate. It absolutely massive and beautifully designed and laid out. You can spend a few days exploring all there is to see. The art museum and the zoo are both free and world class. I had a great time exploring and taking pictures.

This is a fantastic park.  It is larger than Central Park.  The St Louis Zoo is located here.  The naturescape area is really unique.    I haven't seen that before.  My daughter loved it.  I didn't get to see the boatyard, but I did drive by.  It would be a great area for walking, running, biking, etc.

The park is located just off the highway and only a few minutes from downtown.  Also, the zoo is FREE (unless you consider parking).  I truly wish there was a park like this where I live.

Love this place!! It has great walking trails,  gardens, wooded areas and streams through out the park. Great things for the family;  from a great park, a zoo and discovery animals to play and ride on, and picnic areas.  Every part of the park has something to offer! A planetarium,  boat house, jewelbox, zoo, history and art museum all free to the public. Also a golf course for the adults.

Passing through and made a quick stop here. Dog friendly park. Beautiful area to walk around and see the grounds. Zoo is also in this area. I didn't go there but saw the entrance as I was exiting the park. It was beautiful with metal sculptures.

This is a gorgeous park situated in a perfect part of town. Plenty of trails to walk with benches scattered throughout to rest and enjoy nature. Tennis courts, kayaking, canoeing, golf, trails, benches and plenty of open spaces for kites and picnicking make this entire park a picture-perfect spot to relax and explore.

properties.adr_address: 2658 Delmar Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Quaint residence of ragtime composer Scott Joplin, offering period furnishings & a museum.

properties.formatted_address: 2658 Delmar Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA
properties.name: Scott Joplin House State Historic Site

reviews.text:
We really enjoyed our little tour here. We got to learn a lot about Scott Joplin and what St. Louis at that time was like, as well as what life as an itinerant musician was like.

The staff are very friendly and knowledgeable, and I loved getting to listen to an old player piano and finally find out how they work.

They do tours on the hour every hour, so if the website that lets you make reservations only shows tours in the afternoon, call and they’ll add you to a morning tour if you want.

Learned more about Joplins life for the brief period he lived at this address. Also had a wonderful spontaneous performance by an artist Royce Martin who played some of Joplins work and explained the homogenous nature of America's only genre of music invented here.
Generally the neighborhood vibe can leave you feeling uneasy,   there are plenty of run down buildings,   but where the Joplin house is felt good enough to tour the house.

After seeing an informative video, we toured the house.
We were also treated to a superb Ragtime concerto by Royce, who, along with Sarah, answered our many questions in an unhurried manner.
SO GLAD we came!

This is a great museum in the heart of St Louis. Very interesting displays about the life of one of the best African American composers this country has ever known. It's a treat to take the guided tour and learn more about his life and work. There is a piano roll in the museum, and you might get a demo of it if you take the guided tour. Lots of fun. Really friendly staff.

This home rates low in historic value because of the somewhat forced association with renown Ragtime composer Scott Joplin. He rented this home for two years (1901-03) and it was thought he wrote "The Entertainer" here, for which there is little reliable evidence to support the assertion. Making note of this house is akin to saying "George Washington slept here." Joplin was an enormous contributor to American music, with Rag influencing almost all subsequent American music. But this house has little to do with it.

properties.adr_address: 5050 Oakland Ave, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.formatted_address: 5050 Oakland Ave, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.name: St. Louis Science Center Dinosaurs

reviews.text: A good place for an entertaining and educational family outing. It's amazing that you are able to see it free of charge with only occasional extras costing anything. Interesting interactive displays but they are mostly for smaller children. Wish that more hands on things were available for teens or children with an advanced knowledge & interest in science. The bridge between the planetarium and science center is my favorite part.

My family & I really enjoy visiting The Science Center. There are plenty of activities and room to spread out. The new gaming era exhibit they have included really took us back through a trip in time. The farming area outside was a hit as well! This is always a nice free go to on a day to get out of the house.

There's not much they can be said to add to the perfection that is the St Louis science center.

It's free

I've got some of the coolest stuff you'll ever see

It has ever changing attractions and IMAX videos

Has wonderful staff and is always changing. My daughter never ceases the desire to go even if it's only been three or four days.

They have all kind of teachings, visuals and interactions with kiddos, as well as being beautifully and professionally well made. Not quite sure what else you can ask for

This is a great place to visit and learn. There are definitely a lot of activities geared towards kids, but plenty for adults to enjoy. It triggered a lot of nostalgia for me by showing concepts I learned in middle school with hands on displays: energy, tectonic plates, and fossils, to name a few.
It was a fun experience for my 7 year old nephew and for my 3 year old grand daughter. We enjoyed our visit.

properties.adr_address: 5127 Delmar Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63108-1045, USA
properties.formatted_address: 5127 Delmar Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63108, USA
properties.name: The Magic House, MADE for Kids

reviews.text: My family visited for the first time as we were in town for vacation. We got there late so we got to enjoy the reduced pricing. My 9 and 11 year olds had a good time. There was plenty to do and everything is wheelchair accessible. Staff was friendly.

Cute little area for kids who like to be expressive.  Several different areas to explore including legos, clay, art, building, Cricut, and 3D printing.

Pros:
- Price: $5per ticket (everyone including adults pay to enter).  After 3pm price goes does to $3
- Lots to explore, if kids like expressive type activities you could easily spend the afternoon here
- Parking is free.
- There was a pottery demonstration when we were there.

Cons:
- Not an ideal location, parking was across very busy road.
- Many activities came at an additional cost.  Pottery painting, Cricut activities, 3D printing.
- Very small location, gets very loud, not ideal for kids with sensory issues

This place is awesome! The staff is helpful and there is so much to do.  With our 5 kiddos we thought we'd run out of things to do really quickly but we were dead wrong.  We had to drag our kids out of there they loved it so much.  Military discount goes a long way here.  Great people! Great place!
My 8yr old  Loves this place! He is a tech kids and love to create things, I love making things with the clay because you get to keep it! Every you have to pay for is only $5!! Its really amazing!!
The kids (and parents) loved this! There is so much to do and the stations are incredibly well thought out. There is something to do and entertain (while also leaning) for all ages.

properties.adr_address: 1 Fine Arts Dr, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.formatted_address: 1 Fine Arts Dr, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.name: Grace Taylor Broughton Sculpture Park

properties.adr_address: 3352 Demenil Pl, St. Louis, MO 63118-3211, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Circa-1853 Greek Revival mansion with art, artifacts & memorabilia honoring the region's heritage.

properties.formatted_address: 3352 Demenil Pl, St. Louis, MO 63118, USA
properties.name: Chatillon-DeMenil Mansion

reviews.text: Among the dozen historic homes in St. Louis, I find this the most charming. Take the docent-lead tour for a marvelous, knowledgable (probably 1-on-1) narration detailing the owners and this curious, wonderful home. The personal belongings and household fixtures provide an exquisite depiction of the well to do including devices such as the fold-out bathtub and silver wineglass cooling bowl. A modest fee is assessed for admission and the tour.

Very interesting historical home near Anhesher Busch. Guides enhanced experience with background on homeowners and historical pieces in the home. Although one of the guides spoke way too fast and was hard to catch everything.
Great tour guide. Educational and fun.
I had a lovely time at the Bastille Day celebration.  The music was very nice and the dancers were great.  Everyone was so friendly and hospitable.
Must visit if you love historical houses like me 😍

properties.adr_address: 222 Worth Rd, St. Louis, MO 63125-4253, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Commemorative exhibits honoring the Civil War in an historic 1905 former post exchange for soldiers.

properties.formatted_address: 222 Worth Rd, St. Louis, MO 63125, USA
properties.name: Missouri Civil War Museum

reviews.text:
A wonderful museum that will have you leaving humbled and empathetic to a dark time in our nations history.

Great experience and the fact it is in Jefferson Barracks, one of the oldest military installations in the U.S. adds to the experience.

The staff was also extremely helpful and kind. There is also a nice gift shop to conclude the experience.

Looking forward to going back again.

I'm local and embarrassed to say I didn't know this gem exists.  If you're at all interested in the subject, it's fantastic.  The entire project was volunteer/donor funded and executed.  No government funds were used and it's a model of private support for a public good.  On to the museum...

The renovation to the building is of very high quality.  It was originally the Post exchange and Gym, but was used as a hospital ward and various other purposes before sitting empty and in disrepair for years.  Many truly original details are missing, but the mezzanine running track and railing along with a few other great components remain.  What has been replaced is well done and in keeping with the building.

There are two intro videos early on and both are well done.  The first provides background on the building and the second focuses on the Missouri Compromise and other preludes to secession.  It's very much worth watching both and they provide good context for the displays.

The displays are well organized, content is explained in nice bite sized pieces and they are all spotless.  There's representation of both the North and South with the obvious goal to tell the stories of those represented and let the visitor develop their own understanding.

Some objects that surprised me that were great to see:
* A sitting chair that a Union General bought from the estate of Mary Todd Lincoln.
* A cane the same General had made from brass and wood that originated on the USS Constitution (Old Ironsides), the world's oldest ship that is still afloat.  (Her tour in Boston is also Don't Miss.)
* A First Edition of Uncle Tom's Cabin.
* A toy - but functional - black powder cannon made from scrap materials recovered from the Eads Bridge construction.
* A spyglass used at Gettysburg (!!!)
* Other:  LOTS of period weapons in excellent condition, a display medical, um, "technology" of the day and complete uniforms.

If this doesn't get you excited about making plans to go, you probably shouldn't.  Admission was $7 with discounts for students, seniors and members.  I spent about 3 hours and only finished the main floor.  Will go back to walk the lower level.  Bonus in August:  The AC works GREAT!

Upside: friendly staff,  nice weapon display,  gift shop, used books for sale, clean restrooms.
Downside: Dim lighting, closes early (4pm) through the week.
Comments: Would recommend going here, some neat artifacts. Review based on one visit.
Amazing collection in a historical location. It's small, but absolutely worth it. The Abraham Lincoln saber and bronze casting were incredible to see in person.

This place had an overall great overhaul of exhibits ranging from rifles and handguns to equipment, clothing, and books from the civil war era. They also have this really nice souvenir shop with all sorts of books, toys, flags, and hats you can buy. Overall, they represented both sides of the war equally and didn't show any bias against the north or the south. Great museum to visit!

reviews.text: Always a fantastic place to visit. Art Hill is quite beautiful just to relax, see a concert, or have a little picnic with the family or a loved one. I would highly recommend this place, but remember to bring a blanket or something to sit on.

Beautiful section of Forrest Park, which I learned today is actually bigger than Ney York's Central Park. It's the area I'm front of the Art Museum with a statue that used to be the symbol of St Louis before they built the Gateway Arch. Nice place to sit and relax with a good view of a big water fountain.

A must see spot in Forest Park. Great any time of the year. Love seeing people lounge, read, workout, and have picnics.

A lot of people take wedding photos by the water. Also there are some fitness/yoga classes that occur here too.

Art Hill in the winter is something in every St. Louisian should do. What a fantastic joy to watch the families scream down the hills and run into the hay bills at the bottom we took. We went as a family and it was absolutely incredible. Highly recommend to anybody who wants to have a good time

Today is Labor Day. The Flags of Valor have returned. Over the green pastures of Art Hill wave, in a sea of red white and blue, stand this magnificent display of flags with the pictures and dog tags of our American fallen heros from all over the United States of America. Art Hill is already beautiful and well kept. There are also spectacular flowers on display. I recommend anybody who is visiting or lives here to take advantage of this wonderful place. We bring my grandson, who has autism, to Art Hill often.

There was too much mourning/ shaking our history. As someone who loves both history and St Louis, I expected more. The place was nice and informational but the displays could have been better.
Great memorial to a excellent statesman, architect and founding father.
I want stopped in the parking lot. However, the building you can see the inside and it looks really nice. I was lost in St Louis. 🤔
i Liked the architecture and the environment.great place to visit.

The owner is extraordinarily knowledgeable about every item he has, as well as the era from which it came. I absolutely recommend this museum to all people--young or old, black or white, etc.

I love this place because of it vast amount of history.  The Rileys have so much information from people who live in St. louis and made so much impact on the city.  I have gained so much knowledge.  Everyone should take tume to visit this Museum in the heart of the city of St. Louis.
This museum brought back so many memories!  I plan to return with my friends and perhaps conduct a fund raiser.
I learned so much there.  The guided tour was unlike the traditional stuffy musuems that I had experienced.  Totally loved it.🤗😙🤗
Good but not what it used to be. Service is still great and food was hot!!

Was a beautiful location for my wedding, but rigid policies on adding hours to my reception lost them $45-90 and lost us time to dance and have fun. reviews.text: Came for Golf at the Galleries. So much fun and really cool artist designed mini golf course. Reasonable price for kids and adults. They do have concessions and adult* beverages too! Buy tickets online, took us about an hour. Might be a bit hard for kids under 4.

The Sheldon is a world class, St Louis gem. This historical building boasts the best acoustics of any performance hall. In fact, Heather Headley once sand an entire song without a mic and no one had issues hearing her. The Sheldon's mission is "art without borders," they undoubtedly achieve that through the diverse performances and artists who come through. In addition to live musical and dance shows, they have an art gallery that is free to visit! Events like Golf the Gallery are a must see experience, along with any patron level tickets.

The Sheldon is amazing. I hope that every one who comes through our city is able to visit. If you're local and you haven't seen a show, it's worth it. Tickets are always inexpensive and there is literally no bad seat in the house.

We went to the Sheldon to see Charlie Musselwhite and Elvin Bishop and it was a wonderful concert and an intimate show. We had a great time and heard some excellent music interspersed with fun stories from their hundred years of blues. Such a great place to see a concert! We'll be back soon!

The Sheldon is a true St Louis gem! One of the best rooms in the city if not the nation to see and hear live music. The galleries are also very beautiful and offer an amazing space. Loved by patrons and artists alike, don't sleep on this classic!

The Sheldon Concert Hall was a perfect location for listening to the St. Louis Brass Band. The ceiling height in the auditorium as well as the angle of the seats facing the stage really amplified the acoustics. Paired with beautiful sounds is glowing color from the stained glass high on the walls on both sides of the auditorium.

The ticket system was easy to navigate online before the show and there was a line to buy tickets upon entering the building. However, no one checked to see if I had my ticket. I wonder if many snuck into the show for free.

reviews.text: Highly recommend! Especially for those up to age 8 or 9. So much variety of activities. They also have a quiet room that allows an area to take a calming break if needed or a private area for nursing.  My grandson loved all of the activities. Great staff. We could have stayed all day. They have a cafe but there are also good food choices close, so you can take a break and come back.

Had a lot if fun there with my 3yr old granddaughter. Lots to do to keep her going. Staff was on hand watching which was good since older kids were getting out of hand. We will b back soon! Had India theme to show kids different places around the world it was fun and educational.

An amazing children’s museum. Something for everyone. We were able to get through it in a few hours, but definitely could have spent a lot longer exploring. We did split up so we could follow the interests of the children, so if possible, go with multiple adults. I had fun, too, but I can be a big kid, so we had fun playing in the courtroom and Oval Office.

First time visitors with my twins and myself. They had a blast! We luckily arrived after 3pm and there is a deal for advanced tickets online for $3 per person and it was well worth it! There is so much for them to do and play with. The staff here is very friendly and there is something for everyone, including us adults! They have a cafe for quick meals and an outdoor play area. If you're needing something for the Littles to do and burn some energy this place is just for you!  Definitely going to visit again!

we enjoyed our time at the magic house. it was perfect for our 5 year old! the magic house is age appropriate anywhere from age 2 to id say 12. there are many things to do from one floor to the next. They even have a small restaurant "the Lunch Box" with great snack and lunch options for kids and adults. They accommodated my wife with her meal as we are expecting she needed her meat on her sandwich heated up. Very helpful and nice! we finished up at the art area on our way out after visiting the store to get a few keep sakes. This was our last stop after spending 3 nights in St. Louis and plan to make it a stop every time we go. it wrote our daughter out and she napped on the way back on our 4 hour venture home. One note to mention is our daughter does have cerebral palsy and she was able to do everything here. She jumped right in having fun with the other children and enjoyed herself very much!

If you happened to go and did not check out the horror section, you'd absolutely be missing out. It's not a haunted house, but I'd say it's better than one. No, nothing touches you or reaches out, but it's so creepy and weird that it seriously terrified me. I'd recommend this to anyone looking for a fun thing to do that's off the beaten path.

I'm sorry, but this place is weirdly wonderful! If you're looking for Madam Tussauds than you'll be disappointed, but if you're looking for the odd and unusual (which I prefer) than look no more! I have been coming here for 25 years and it always leaves a lasting impression!
