reviews.text: It's cool to see. I don't know that I'd need to do it more than once.  Buy tickets in advance. You can also check the website around 900a and see if they are any available tickets.  I checked and got a ticket for the same day.  You have to go through security as it's a national landmark.  They have a museum area after that and other setups to learn about the arch and its history, there is a gift shop and cafe inside.  Line up at your time... there aren't many people lining up until about 4-5 min prior to the scheduled time. You stand in line for a while before you get to go back. There really isn't a benefit because you get assigned a group 1 through 9. You sit with your group in the pod up and down...maximum of 5 people

Wonderful experience!  It was cool driving through town and seeing the arch get bigger and bigger as we got closer.  Then to be standing under it was amazing.  The view from the top and museum were fabulous. The tram ride was faster than expected. We’ll worth the time and Money!

Well done National Park Service! I bought tickets online about a month ahead of time. I was able to have the tickets on my phone. We arrived about 30 to 45 minutes ahead of our tour time to allow for the security check. At the appointed time we were directed through the tour. The tour guides were courteous and very helpful answering questions. The views from the top are spectacular and for me, well worth the price of admission. The ride up and down is a little bumpy and the pod is a little claustrophobic, but should be no problem for most people. There is a historical museum after entry and before or after the tour that is worth a walk through. There is a concession stand of sorts as well as a souvenir shop. Overall, a great experience!

I recently went on an adventure to St. Louis where we had the opportunity to visit the Gateway Arch. This grand stainless steel monument, completed in 1965, stands at an impressive height of 630 feet and is an iconic representation of mid-century modern design that symbolizes our national identity.
During our visit, we managed to capture some incredible shots of the arch, from the outside, the observation platform, and even from inside the underground museum. Lastly, a depiction of the tiny barrel that takes you to the top really is, which was a little amusing considering the grandeur of the arch.
The museum was a pleasant surprise, as it was filled with fascinating information on the Native Americans who were impacted by St. Louis's role in westward expansion. We were impressed with the care and polish used in the presentation of the past, which helped make it a memorable and educational experience.
Overall, our adventure to the Gateway Arch was an absolute blast. It's no wonder that it's a must-see attraction in St. Louis, and we highly recommend it to anyone.

Had a great time here with my husband, son and myself. My son and I made it to the top of the arch. The tram ride up was so unique. The top had  good views and it was quite the experience. You get about 10 minutes at the top which seemed like plenty of time. It was windy and rainy that day so we could feel the sway. The museum is so nice. And the documentary was full of great info.

reviews.text: An amazing National Park, much smaller than most parks but still has plenty to offer. If you are here to get to the top of the arch then you are in for a good time. The whole experience if fantastic and the top has some great views. Underneath the arch there is a great museum and plenty of historical artifacts. The park itself is also amazing, has plenty of trees and walking areas. There is a riverfront and pond to walk near as well. Quiet and peaceful overall.

What a wonderful experience it was. When we decided to come to see the arch we had know idea what to expect. Absolutely breath taking and the history and meaning behind it is just inspiring. It was a great day from the arrival in the city until we left. This whole experience is something I never imagined and the views from the arch are stunning. After the tour we went to the movie and the museum and it was all fascinating. What a great place and a must see for everyone.

This was the favorite attraction on our visit to St Louis. We reserved our tram tickets well in advance online. We got to the museum, got in line and only had to wait about 10 minutes for our tour to start. Our group was small and because of covid you currently get to ride in the pods with just your party which was nice as they are super tiny and would be no fun with strangers. The views from the top are amazing. Plenty of time to take pictures in the 8 minutes you get up there. We were on the North tram. The group that came up from the south tram was much larger so it's all luck of the draw. A smaller group with a nice for us because you can choose any of the windows to look out of on the top without being crowded. Each pod has a window for a door so you can see the inner workings of the arch which we thought was super cool! Everyone was super friendly. We got drinks and the huge pretzel from the cafe. Very expensive for a pretzel and drinks. Parking was only $9 in the East stadium lot for 5 hours which is only a couple blocks away and an easy walk. Plenty of time to look through the nicely done Museum, do the tram ride to the top, eat something at the cafe, and explore a neighboring Park!

The only word that comes to mind to describe the Gateway Arch National Park is "Indescribable!"  The history of the territory and architecture of the arch, the panoramic view of Missouri and of the Mississippi are indescribably awesome!  The museum is easy to tour, the movie is a must see, and the riverboat ride is an excellent touch.  The staff is extremely helpful and professional.  Do be prepared for federal government style security checks when entering the park.  Tour pricing is based upon what attractions you want to see and scheduling is set to accommodate your arrival and departure time frames.

What a fun place to visit! It may be the smallest
National Park, but they pack a lot in this area. The museum was incredibly informative and I learned a lot. The tram ride to the top was thrilling. It offered one-of-a-kind views of the city and would recommend to anyone. Well the tram may be small, the ride went by very quick. I would recommend a pair of headphones to help distract you if you are claustrophobic. The museum staff and park rangers answered every question I had and even offered some additional advice. When I went, the old courthouse was still being renovated and was closed.

The young lady that answers the phone not only is NO help please don't interupt her on her lunch or a bad day then you will not get any help. I have been trying to contact both the Director that stated should could not afford the venue and caters. She has yet to respond to my emails nor phone calls. Because of this horrible experience not only has my blood pressure went up which is not good for me nor my unborn but now I have so little time to find another venue with such short notice. If you are looking to spend over $2500 for a small baby shower be my guest. I just know my fiance and I are not only planning a wedding for next year with yes with both income with a child and another on the way but we are do not have budget for this at all.

It looks nice from the outside and is probably a beautiful venue for any event, but the woman who books the events was extremely rude to me over the phone. Even if I could have my event there, I wouldn't because I would not want to have to work with her. If you do call, be aware that it is pronounced KA-bonnie, not ka-BONNIE.

Not open to the public

Pretty cool place. Nice the city sets this aside for people. I have seen a few nice ones in Austin, San Diego, but this is the largest. Some great artwork, but of course idiots tagging great work with garbage really takes away from something special. Still totally worth checking it out.

Awesome place for a photo shoot of any kind.

The detail is beautiful. Definitely a must see

This place was so dope. I wasn't able to walk the entire mural but what I was able to walk was amazing.  It's nice the city allows things like this. Definitely want to go back on a cooler day and check out the artwork

A waste of time.   Some of the worst and trashes murals, er. tags. that I've see.  Don't waste your time.  Go see the exhibit in Miami Florida, it's regulated and only professional murals.  The kids at this one in St Louis would do better tagging trashcans.

reviews.text: Overall a very nice museum to visit. Mostly trains and cars, but there are other items as well. Some very unique pieces such as a fabulous custom car owned by Bobby Darin and the world's largest tanker car. They also let you get into the cab of a Big Boy. A couple of issues: The price is on the high side (not outrageous, but high) but then they continue to nickel and dime you with other activities. Plus a lot of the best train cars were not accessible to see on the inside, so you had to try to look through windows, which didn't work very well. Finally know that there is a lot of walking and climbing involved.

Everyone was very nice and it was a good way to spend an afternoon. Train ride was fun and for $5 you get as many rides as you want until the rides are done. Make sure to visit all the buildings (you can only see them all if you get a map). We missed two buildings and still spent 2-3 hours here. (We read all the signs and took our time too... It can be done quicker if you want)

Impromptu visit as we were originally on our way somewhere else. My sons second time here but my first. I was very pleased with the knowledge one of the volunteers had on the subject of trains. He gave me a lot of awesome information and things to look into for when my son is older. Everywhere was clean and well kept.

It was amazing to see all the old cars and trains. I have to say the miniature train ride was pretty lame because it was so generic. There were some trains you can go into but most of them were just there for you to see and photograph. Cool and unique place to go in St. Louis.

We traveled across the country to see the big boy as we are seeing them all. We enjoyed seeing all the trains and discovering a GG1 was also there. The sibling to the daylight is there as well. Great museum. Wish the big boy was covered so it ages better.

reviews.text: Great space for an event with all the plants hanging about. There are bathrooms in the back and down the stairs. The history of the place is also really cool as it dates back to 1916! It does cost $1 to walk around the place on a normal day but it’s worth it. The lily pond out front is also fun to walk around. The grounds are kept up beautifully.

The Jewel Box in Forest Park is a lovely horticultural greenhouse with lovely displays throughout the year. They are open:
Monday through Thursday, from 9 a.m. to 4 p.m.
Friday from 9 a.m. to 3 p.m.
Saturday, from 9 to 11 a.m.
Sunday, from 9 a.m. to 2 p.m
Admission is $1 per person, but it is free on Monday and Tuesday from 9 a.m. until noon.

A lovely treat inside and out, especially in late Spring and summer when the lily pond is active and the outdoor flowers are bursting in bloom!

A Saint Louis treat in beautiful Forest Park.
Beautiful - Tulips are in bloom now and are a must see.  Have been to a wedding here and it was amazing.

I had my wedding here on February 4, 2023 and it was perfect. I got so many compliments on the venue. The man working on the night of my rehearsal was very kind and knowledgeable when I had questions. The doors were even open early for both my rehearsal and wedding, and that was so appreciated with it being chilly outside. I would 100% recommend having your wedding ceremony at the Jewel Box.

The entrance is gorgeous. So many beautiful flowers blooming during the summer. Wonderful place to take family and friends. A lot of benches to rest at while looking at the flowers. The inside is even more beautiful. It is open year round and all week long. Overall a great experience.

Judging on trash and empty Hennessey bottles this place was super busy a night before. I liked their sculptures. Very liked their flowerbeds with different kinds of fragrant herbs.  They have interesting water features.

Such a beautiful spot tucked into downtown St. Louis! The garden has pools for splashing, zen spaces, lots of benches, and co art sculptures to enjoy. Enjoy it for free any day!--no matter the season or the weather. There's always something to enjoy at the Citygarden Sculpture Park.

This is a cool, gorgeous city garden right in the heart of STL. It’s a small garden with many artsy sculptures. We visited in
The time of Christmas, and so they have a nice Christmas lighting. We parked the car on the street. It was weekend, and the parking was cheap. The park is small. It doesn’t take much time to take a walk. There are nice spots to take pictures too.
I had a good experience here.  I went on a Friday evening and there were kids playing in the pools.. its a fun space to walk around. ...its right downtown and it's worth checking out

OMG……. So Relaxing and Picturesque…there are Sculptures that you can take photos on or of…. VERY WELL KELPT area. This is a place to go to enjoy the weather, the view of the arch or just to read a book, yoga, meditation. I recommend this location just to enjoy life in general.

properties.adr_address: 6539 Delmar Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63130, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Life-sized statue of rock 'n' roll legend Chuck Berry, with moving colored lights & engraved lyrics.

properties.formatted_address: 6539 Delmar Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63130, USA
properties.name: Chuck Berry Statue

reviews.text: Great place for a photo opportunity with the beautiful, larger than life-size,  bronze of the inimitable Mr. Chuck Berry. It's right across the street from Blueberry  Hill where the St. Louis and rock and roll icon performed regularly until the late 2010's.
One of the earliest pioneers of hard rock
Awesome Place To See!
Amazing. Chuck was THE man who started it all. RocknRoll baby.

Historical. Area around statute seems to always be well maintained. From time to time you get different types of street performers around the statue which is nice. Also it is right next to Fitz's. So if you are hungry you can eat at Fitz's or you can also walk the other way and get a bite over at salt and smoke. Salt and amoke has outside seating.

properties.adr_address: 6504 Delmar Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63130-4501, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Modeled after its Hollywood namesake, this star-studded sidewalk commemorates noteworthy locals.

properties.formatted_address: 6504 Delmar Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63130, USA
properties.name: St. Louis Walk of Fame

reviews.text: Walk of fame is awesome. Make sure you see Chuck Berry statue!
The walk of fame gave extra thing to do while walking down the street. So many fun places to visit. Awesome for date night. Family friendly street.
Fun to walk along and see all the stars!

This is a great place. Don't miss the Blueberry Hill Restaurant. The pictures inside of all the celebrities with Joe Edwards, and all of the collectible pieces are worth the visit. Also the Moon Rise Hotel is a treat.

Hopefully the street car will be going there from downtown soon.
Awesome to see! Really neat and worth the stop. The Delmar Loop is fantastic for walking around and enjoying the businesses and fresh air.

properties.adr_address: 5200 Delmar Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63108-1028, USA

editorial_summary.overview: This artisan glass gallery & studio offers classes plus monthly events with music & demonstrations.

properties.formatted_address: 5200 Delmar Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63108, USA
properties.name: Third Degree Glass Factory

reviews.text: I went to the Glass Factory for the Riverfront Times inaugural Sugar Rush Event, so I was able to snack on desserts during my visit. Overall I enjoyed the venue, and the art work was beautiful! Watching the glass blowing demonstration was spectacular, the artists were patient, swift and diligent. I could feel the heat from the materials sitting in the front row, so I could only imagine how they felt! The lollipop turned out great. Thanks for an awesome show!

Enjoyed the glass blowing presentation during my visit to STL for a conference. The artist was really good at explaining the various stages of making a sculpture. The staff were very friendly. Had a good chat with one of the artists. They also have pretty awesome gifts to get for friends and family. You ought to go if you’re in the STL area!

My wife and I wanted something unique to do in St Louis so we took a glass blowing lesson. We had a blast and our instructor James was very informative and patient. We highly recommend Third Degree Glass for a new experience and ask for James.

Surprise 60th Birthday party.  The staff was more than accommodating from event planning services to the staff being available and supportive during clean up.  The service and feeling welcomed was superb.  The bartenders Lauren and Dove made every drink special and kept up with the crowd without skipping a beat. The space alone is so beautiful and modern that you don’t need a lot to decorate.   Third Degree Glass Factory Rocks!!
Amazing artwork at reasonable prices.  You can talk to the artists while they're working.  Friendly staff, very helpful.  Highest recommendation!

properties.adr_address: 6500 Government Dr, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.formatted_address: 6500 Government Dr, St. Louis, MO 63110, USA
properties.name: John F. Kennedy Memorial Forest

reviews.text:
About as close to a forest oasis you are going to get within city limits. We were here in the winter so the pictures are not doing it justice. Some parts are deep enough in the woods where you don't see cars or building anymore.

Combination of concrete, gravel, and dirt paths throughout. Trails are kind of a cluster that go off in crazy directions without a real loop. If you do the actual quasi loop I thinks it's barely a mile.
Great place to hike and meditate. Tranquility and Peace are abundant in this hidden gem in the heart of our urban forest.
Great birding and lots of wildlife.

This is one of the most relaxing places to get away and it's hidden right in the middle of the city. When you're deep inside the densely packed forest, you can hardly hear the nearby highway or any city noises, just birds and the wind. There's multiple walking trails and bike trails, bridges and streams. I visit the forest multiple times a week to recharge and center myself. Especially beautiful and lush in the Spring.

Hidden gem in Forest Park. Trails are rarely crowded, and the ecological restoration has produced wonderful results. The wooded areas are full of native wildflowers in spring, and the savanna areas are full of native flowers in summer. Urban oasis of wildlife.

properties.adr_address: 1424 Washington Ave, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA
properties.formatted_address: 1424 Washington Ave, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA
properties.name: The Selfie Room

reviews.text: I love the Selfie Room!!! One of my favorite places in St. Louis! I always have so much fun there. They have cool and unique rooms/backdrops to take photos and videos with, and they change it seasonally so there's aways a reason to come back for more. I walk away with so much content after a visit there. The staff are always super friendly and helpful too. Everything is always clean and organized in the space as well! I highly recommend checking this place out!

Such a great time! I hosted a holiday workout event here and was blown away with the details in the various room set ups! The friendliness of the staff from booking to actual event time was wonderful! The cleanliness and organization of the spaces was great! We will be back!
This was my first time at the Selfie Room and it was Doggy Day! I had a great time taking pics of me and my furbaby! Can't wait to go back for their new Fall themed rooms!

Staff was super nice, the rooms were really cool. They have to order new stands though, I paid for the stand and every single one I received was crooked and it was nearly impossible to get a straight photo. I feel like I wasted my money on that and I wasn’t able to get great pictures with my significant other, and that was the main reason I got the stand. I even had to add a card to the stand to make it more straight.
Such a fun place! The staff is so very helpful too. We loved trying to find the secret room. They will tell you all about it when you visit. I can’t wait to go back!

properties.adr_address: 615 N Grand Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA
properties.formatted_address: 615 N Grand Blvd, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA
properties.name: Nijinski Hare sculpture

reviews.text: The statue Nijinski Hare marries Flanagan’s ever-present hare motif found in many of his bronzes (in the 1980s, he “perceived the image of a hare unveiling itself” before him and has used it since) with a playful and unique interpretation of Vaslav Nijinski, the world famous Russian ballet dancer.
GORGEOUS RABBIT

properties.adr_address: 1015 Sappington Rd, St. Louis, MO 63126, USA

editorial_summary.overview: Restored, furnished Federal-style home built in 1808 offering tours & a gift shop on scenic grounds.

properties.formatted_address: 1015 Sappington Rd, St. Louis, MO 63126, USA
properties.name: Thomas Sappington House Museum

reviews.text: Beautiful home from the early 1800s. The tour was very well done and informative. The Barn restaurant, a library, and Grant's Trail are nearby.
Very interesting place.

Crestwood’s most beautiful hidden gem!! Volunteers keep the grounds looking gorgeous. This a wonderful place to take children to run around and for adults to be at peace in nature. The tour inside the home is fun and great for children.  Don’t forget to walk through the flower garden!

This is a completely charming historic house that has been very thoughtfully renovated to show how it was to live there long ago. The guides are fantastic. This is a real gem you could include in a lovely day out, with a nature trail and a restaurant and an historical library all in the same easy complex.

The docents who were there were very willing to give a tour. They went over the history of the house and the Sappingtons who lived at the house. They mainly focused on what live was like back in the earlier half of the 1800s and were better versed on that than on the house. Still the tour was good.

properties.adr_address: 3415 Olive St, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA
properties.formatted_address: 3415 Olive St, St. Louis, MO 63103, USA
properties.name: International Photography Hall of Fame

reviews.text: As a photographer myself I can’t express what a great experience I had here. I love that they feature local photographers and the important projects they dedicate themselves. It was quite a journey walking the gallery and learning more and more about photography.
Pretty nice museum but did expect something larger. Was happy they are displaying History of St Louis baseball and History of Baseball. Some very nice pics.
A wonderful place to visit and stroll if you're at all interested in photography. Friendly staff, interesting info and great examples from people who know photography. Humbling, to say the least
Exceptional Vivian Maier exhibit, staff was friendly, polite, knowledgeable and all books and prints were 50% off. A great addition to our wonderful city of St Louis. Cheers!
Excellent array of photographs but the facility was much smaller than I anticipated.
